'''Graham Neil Westley''' (born 4 March 1968) is an English former [[association football|footballer]] and is currently [[manager (football)|manager]] of [[Football League Two|League Two]] outfit [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]], where he has been in charge since 2008, his second spell at the club. 

Westley started his managerial career at the age of 28, managing [[Kingstonian F.C.|Kingstonian]] for five months, before spending a year in charge of [[Enfield F.C.|Enfield]]. In 1999, Westley became manager of [[Farnborough Town F.C.|Farnborough Town]], guiding them to the [[Conference National]] in 2002. He left Farnborough the following season, to become manager of Stevenage. He took the club to within one game of promotion to [[the Football League]], but left the club in 2006 when his contract expired. Westley then had a brief, but successful, spell with [[Rushden & Diamonds F.C.|Rushden & Diamonds]], as well as acting as [[caretaker manager]] at [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]]. He took a year out of the game, before rejoining Stevenage in May 2008. He guided the club to [[FA Trophy]] success in [[2009 FA Trophy Final|2009]], before securing promotion to the Football League for the first time in the club's history in April 2010, finishing the season as league champions.

==Playing career==
Westley was born in [[Hounslow]], [[London]] and he started his [[association football|footballing]] career as an apprentice with [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] before joining [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] in March 1986.<ref name="PFA 649"/> He made two league appearances for the club before joining [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]].<ref name="Gillingham : 1950/51 - 2006/07">{{cite news
| title = Gillingham : 1950/51 - 2006/07
| url = http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/gillingham/gillingham.htm
| publisher = Post War English & Scottish Football League A - Z Player's Database
| accessdate = 2007-10-05}}</ref> He made three appearances and scored one goal for them in the [[Conference National|Football Conference]] during the [[1987<U+2013>88 in English football|1987&ndash;88]] season, making his debut for the club in a 2&ndash;2 draw against [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]] at [[Moss Rose]].<ref name="Alliance to Conference 1979-2004: The First 25 Years 71-75">{{cite book
 | last = Harman
 | first = John
 | title = Alliance to Conference 1979-2004: The First 25 Years
 | publisher = Tony Williams Publications
 | year = 2005
 | pages = 71&ndash;75
 | isbn = 186983352X }}</ref><ref name="A look at previous meetings between the Bees & the Silkmen">{{cite news
| title = A look at previous meetings between the Bees & the Silkmen
| url = http://www.barnet-mad.co.uk/feat/edz4/past_times_macclesfield_town_514347/index.shtml
| publisher = Barnet F.C
| accessdate = 2010-04-07
| accessdate = 2010-06-09}}</ref> Westley left Barnet when his short-term contract expired, and joined [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]] in the latter stages of 1987, where he played a total of 20 times, scoring 4 goals during the club's 1987&ndash;88 campaign.<ref name="A look at previous meetings between the Bees & the Silkmen">{{cite news
| title = A look at previous meetings between the Bees & the Silkmen
| url = http://www.barnet-mad.co.uk/feat/edz4/past_times_macclesfield_town_514347/index.shtml
| publisher = Barnet Mad
| accessdate = 2010-04-07
| accessdate = 2010-06-09}}</ref> He later played for a number of [[non-League football|non-League]] clubs, including [[Kingstonian F.C.|Kingstonian]], [[Wealdstone F.C.|Wealdstone]], [[Farnborough Town F.C.|Farnborough Town]], [[Harlow Town F.C.|Harlow Town]], [[Enfield F.C.|Enfield]], [[Aylesbury United F.C.|Aylesbury United]], [[Harrow Borough F.C.|Harrow Borough]], [[Tooting & Mitcham United F.C.|Tooting & Mitcham United]], [[Molesey F.C.|Molesey]] and [[Walton & Hersham F.C.|Walton & Hersham]] &ndash; three of which he would later go on to manage.<ref name="Triggs">{{cite book |   first=Roger|last= Triggs |   title=The Men Who Made Gillingham Football Club|   publisher=Tempus Publishing Ltd |   year=2001|   id=ISBN 0-7524-2243-X|page=332}}</ref> During his time at Kingstonian, he suffered a dislocated ankle and broken leg in three places, which subsequently cut his playing career short after never fully recovering from the injury.<ref name="Graham Westley column">{{cite book
 | last = 
 | first = 
 | title = Graham Westley column
 | publisher = Non-League Paper
 | year = 2009
 | page = 16
 | isbn = }}</ref> On his playing career, Westley said "I felt sorry for myself too often when I should have been leading the team".<ref name="I will make the Sun shine">{{cite news
| title = I will make the Sun shine
| url = http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/sport/football/article197728.ece
| publisher = ''The Sun''
| accessdate = 2003-01-04
| accessdate = 2010-07-04}}</ref>

==Managerial career==
===Early management===
While recovering from a broken leg, at the age of 28,<ref name="Graham Westley">{{cite book
 | last = 
 | first = 
 | title = Graham Westley
 | publisher = Non-League Paper
 | year = 2010
 | page = 11
 | isbn = }}</ref> Westley was appointed as manager of [[Kingstonian F.C.|Kingstonian]] in December 1996 after approaching the club about their vacant managerial post.<ref name="Graham Westley column">{{cite book
 | last = 
 | first = 
 | title = Graham Westley column
 | publisher = Non-League Paper
 | year = 2010
 | page = 22
 | isbn = }}</ref> His first two games in-charge of the club both ended in 4&ndash;4 draws against [[Walton & Hersham F.C.|Walton & Hersham]] and [[Harrow Borough F.C.|Harrow Borough]] respectively,<ref name="Graham Westley">{{cite book
 | last = 
 | first = 
 | title = Graham Westley
 | publisher = Non-League Paper
 | year = 2010
 | page = 11
 | isbn = }}</ref> with Westley saying "at the time, there was something raw and exciting about the team that I sent out. Although there was also something evidently missing".<ref name="Graham Westley">{{cite book
 | last = 
 | first = 
 | title = Graham Westley
 | publisher = Non-League Paper
 | year = 2010
 | page = 11
 | isbn = }}</ref> His first victory in-charge of the club was a 2&ndash;0 win over [[Wokingham Town F.C.|Wokingham Town]] in the [[Isthmian League|Isthmian League Cup]],<ref name="Fixture List- 1996/1997">{{cite news
| title = Fixture List- 1996/1997
| url = http://www.kingstonian.net/fixtures.jsp?19961997
| publisher = Kingstonian F.C.
| accessdate = 2010-07-11}}</ref> before securing his first league win in the following game, a 5&ndash;2 win away at [[Aylesbury United F.C.|Aylesbury United]].<ref name="Fixture List- 1996/1997">{{cite news
| title = Fixture List- 1996/1997
| url = http://www.kingstonian.net/fixtures.jsp?19961997
| publisher = Kingstonian F.C.
| accessdate = 2010-07-11}}</ref> Kingstonian drew clear of relegation, with Westley recalling a 3&ndash;2 victory over champions [[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil Town]] at [[Huish Park]] as a "memorable victory".<ref name="Graham Westley">{{cite book
 | last = 
 | first = 
 | title = Graham Westley
 | publisher = Non-League Paper
 | year = 2010
 | page = 11
 | isbn = }}</ref> Despite securing safety for the club, he was sacked after just five months at the club, being replaced by [[Geoff Chapple]].<ref name="Football: Enfield turn back to Westley and Pearce">{{cite news
| title = Football: Enfield turn back to Westley and Pearce 
| url = http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-enfield-turn-back-to-westley-and-pearce-1241283.html
| publisher = ''The Independent''
| accessdate = 1997-09-26
| accessdate = 2010-07-04}}</ref> He managed Kingstonian for 25 games in total; recording nine wins, eight losses, and eight draws.<ref name="Fixture List- 1996/1997">{{cite news
| title = Fixture List- 1996/1997
| url = http://www.kingstonian.net/fixtures.jsp?19961997
| publisher = Kingstonian F.C.
| accessdate = 2010-07-11}}</ref>

In September 1997, Westley was appointed as manager of another club he had previously played for in the form of [[Isthmian League Premier Division]] outfit [[Enfield F.C.|Enfield]]. He appointed Graham Pearce as his assistant, who had also previously played for, and managed, Enfield.<ref name="Football: Enfield turn back to Westley and Pearce">{{cite news
| title = Football: Enfield turn back to Westley and Pearce 
| url = http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-enfield-turn-back-to-westley-and-pearce-1241283.html
| publisher = Independent.co.uk
| accessdate = 1997-09-26
| accessdate = 2010-07-04}}</ref> He outlined his ambition of ensuring the club returned to the top tier in non-league, despite a host of financial difficulties at the club, he stated "my ambition is to see silverware in the table, and if you can't take the pressure, you shouldn't take big jobs like this one".<ref name="Football: Enfield turn back to Westley and Pearce">{{cite news
| title = Football: Enfield turn back to Westley and Pearce 
| url = http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-enfield-turn-back-to-westley-and-pearce-1241283.html
| publisher = ''Independent.co.uk''
| accessdate = 1997-09-26
| accessdate = 2010-07-04}}</ref> His first game as manager of Enfield was a 2&ndash;0 home defeat to [[St Albans City F.C.|St Albans City]].<ref name="Ryman Premier 1997-1998 results">{{cite news
| title = Ryman Premier 1997-1998 results
| url = http://www.tonykempster.co.uk/archive97-98/rympres.htm
| publisher = Tony Kempster
| accessdate = 2010-07-11}}</ref> Despite securing a 7th placed finish for the club, Westley left the club after just nine months in charge.<ref name="I will make the Sun shine">{{cite news
| title = I will make the Sun shine
| url = http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/sport/football/article197728.ece
| publisher = The Sun.co.uk
| accessdate = 2003-01-04
| accessdate = 2010-07-04}}</ref><ref name="Non-league Football Tables, 1889-2008">{{cite book
 | last = Blakeman
 | first = Mick
 | title = Non-league Football Tables, 1889-2008
 | publisher = Soccer Books Ltd; 7 Rev Ed edition
 | year = 2008
 | page = 63
 | isbn = 1862231710}}</ref> He managed the club for a total of 34 games; winning 15, losing 14, and drawing 5 &ndash; with a win percentage of 44.12%.<ref name="Ryman Premier 1997-1998 results">{{cite news
| title = Ryman Premier 1997-1998 results
| url = http://www.tonykempster.co.uk/archive97-98/rympres.htm
| publisher = Tony Kempster
| accessdate = 2010-07-11}}</ref>

===Farnborough Town===
In 1999, Westley bought a controlling interest in [[Farnborough Town F.C.|Farnborough Town]] and appointed himself as [[manager (football)|manager]].<ref name="Triggs" /><ref name="Graham Westley's managerial career">{{cite news
| title = Graham Westley's managerial career
| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/managers2.sd?managerid=1850
| publisher = Soccerbase
| accessdate = 2007-10-05}}</ref> He managed the club to a 12th place finish in his first season in charge, but enjoyed success in the [[Isthmian League Premier Division|Isthmian Cup]]; winning the competition in 2000.<ref name="Westley quits Farnborough">{{cite news
| title = Westley quits Farnborough
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/2703141.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2003-01-28
| accessdate = 2007-10-05}}</ref> The following season, Westley guided the club to more success, winning the [[Isthmian League Premier Division]]; securing 31 victories out of a possible 42 and amassing a total of 99 points.<ref name="Farnborough Town - FCHD">{{cite news
| title = Farnborough Town - FCHD
| url = http://www.fchd.btinternet.co.uk/FARNBORT.HTM
| publisher = Football Club History Database
| accessdate = 2010-05-13}}</ref> Westley overhauled the squad shortly after the club's promotion to the [[Conference National]] &ndash; something which he now states as a "huge regret".<ref name="The Non-League Show podcast">{{cite news
| title = The Non-League Show podcast
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/london/hi/tv_and_radio/newsid_8176000/8176112.stm
| publisher = BBC London
| accessdate = 2010-05-13}}</ref> At this point, he also tried to arrange a merger with [[Kingstonian F.C.|Kingstonian]] &ndash; citing the club's "Football League rated ground" as the reasoning behind his proposed idea, although it never happened due to "fans resistance".<ref name="Westley puts his faith in the right attitude">{{cite news
| title = Westley puts his faith in the right attitude
| url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2394935/Westley-puts-his-faith-in-the-right-attitude.html
| publisher = ''The Daily Telegraph''
| date = 2003-01-23
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref>  During the [[2001<U+2013>02 in English football|2001&ndash;02]] season, the club consolidated their position in the first tier of non&ndash;league football; with Westley guiding the club to a 7th place finish in the league. The following season was to be a memorable campaign for Westley, reaching the Third Round of the [[FA Cup]] after a 3&ndash;0 victory at [[Southport F.C.|Southport]], where they faced [[the Football League|Football League]] competition in the form of [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] at [[Feethams]].<ref name="Southport 0-3 Farnboro">{{cite news
| title = Southport 0-3 Farnboro
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/2530801.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2002-12-07
| accessdate = 2010-05-22}}</ref> Westley guided the side to a 3&ndash;2 win over Darlington, and the club were rewarded with a Fourth Round tie at home to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref name="Farnborough shock Quakers">{{cite news
| title = Farnborough shock Quakers
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/2607201.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2003-02-13
| accessdate = 2010-05-22}}</ref> The tie, however, was controversially moved to [[Arsenal_Stadium|Highbury]] &ndash; due to the fact that the tie stood to make around <U+00A3>600,000 in gate receipts from playing at Highbury, whereas playing at [[Cherrywood Road]] would only have generated the club an estimated <U+00A3>50,000.<ref name="Are you happy with Farnborough's fixture?">{{cite news
| title = Are you happy with Farnborough's fixture? 
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/sports_talk/2638157.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2003-01-08
| accessdate = 2010-05-22}}</ref> Westley left the club after the sell-out 'home' tie at Highbury, which they lost 5&ndash;1.<ref name="Debt threat to Borough FC">{{cite news
| title = Debt threat to Borough FC
| url = http://www.gethampshire.co.uk/news/s/36398_debt_threat_to_borough_fc__by_cliff_mogg
| publisher = ''GetHampshire''
| accessdate = 2008-08-05}}</ref><ref name="Arsenal cruise through">{{cite news
| title = Arsenal cruise through
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/2671825.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| accessdate = 2010-05-22}}</ref> Shortly after his resignation, he became manager at [[Conference National]] rivals [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]] in January 2003, signing a three-year contract. Westley confirmed he would be leaving his shareholding in Farnborough to other existing shareholders, and would also be withdrawing his financial backing at the club.<ref name="Westley quits Farnborough">{{cite news
| title = Westley quits Farnborough
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/2703141.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2003-01-28
| accessdate = 2007-10-05}}</ref> On moving to Stevenage, Westley said "I've enjoyed my time at Farnborough, but I feel that I need to move on now and that I need to concentrate on football management, which is where my ambitions lie".<ref name="Westley happy to move on">{{cite news
| title = Westley happy to move on
| url = http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/westley-happy-to-move-on-609056.html
| publisher = Independent Sport
| date = 2003-01-31
| accessdate = 2010-06-09}}</ref> He went on to state that Stevenage's "long-term potential" was another key factor behind the move.<ref name="Westley happy to move on">{{cite news
| title = Westley happy to move on
| url = http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/westley-happy-to-move-on-609056.html
| publisher = Independent Sport
| date = 2003-01-31
| accessdate = 2010-06-09}}</ref>

===Stevenage===
When Westley took over the [[Hertfordshire]] club, [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]] were sitting 21st in the [[Conference National]], and were six points adrift of safety.<ref name="Westley quits Farnborough">{{cite news
| title = Westley quits Farnborough
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/2703141.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2003-01-28
| accessdate = 2007-10-05}}</ref> Unlike his position at his previous club, Westley was appointed as first-team manager, with no board involvement.<ref name="Westley quits Farnborough">{{cite news
| title = Westley quits Farnborough
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/2703141.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2003-01-28
| accessdate = 2007-10-05}}</ref> He set about ensuring the club were still in the highest tier in non-league football, signing seven players from his previous club Farnborough, as well as his former assistant Graham Pearce and goalkeeping coach [[Graham Benstead]].<ref name="Manager Guide - Graham Westley">{{cite news
| title = Manager Guide - Graham Westley 
| url = http://www.boroguide.co.uk/players/managers/westley_graham.php
| publisher = Boroguide
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref><ref name="Westley happy to move on">{{cite news
| title = Westley happy to move on
| url = http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/westley-happy-to-move-on-609056.html
| publisher = Independent Sport
| date = 2003-01-31
| accessdate = 2010-06-09}}</ref> His first game in charge of the club was a 1&ndash;1 draw at home to [[Morecambe F.C.|Morecambe]],<ref name="Stevenage 1-1 Morecambe">{{cite news
| title = Stevenage 1-1 Morecambe
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/2716147.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2003-02-13
| accessdate = 2010-05-22}}</ref> before having to wait three games for his first win at the club &ndash; a 2&ndash;0 victory away at local rivals [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]], thanks to a [[Dino Maamria]] brace.<ref name="Barnet 0-2 Stevenage">{{cite news
| title = Barnet 0-2 Stevenage
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/2805157.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2003-03-08
| accessdate = 2010-05-22}}</ref> The victory sparked an eight game unbeaten run, recording six victories on the bounce to ensure the club were safe from relegation.<ref name="Burton 1-2 Stevenage">{{cite news
| title = Burton 1-2 Stevenage
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/2917931.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2003-04-12
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> Westley had guided the club from 21st in the table to a respectable 12th place finish by the end of the season.<ref name="Final 2002/2003 Football Conference Table">{{cite news
| title = Final 2002/2003 Football Conference Table
| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/league2.sd
| publisher = Soccerbase
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> The [[2003-04 in English football|2003&ndash;04]] season witnessed a much more consistent season under Westley's management, but the club were unable to make the play-offs and finished the campaign in 8th place, despite a positive start to the season.<ref name="Final 2003/2004 Football Conference Table">{{cite news
| title = Final 2003/2004 Football Conference Table
| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/league2.sd
| publisher = Soccerbase
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> 

As was the case in previous seasons, Westley made wholesale changes at the end of the season, releasing several of the players he had originally signed from Farnborough, and replacing them with a mixture of players with Football League experience &ndash; in the form of [[Brian Quailey]],<ref name="Stevenage snap up Quailey">{{cite news
| title = Stevenage snap up Quailey
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/2917931.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2004-04-20
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> [[Dannie Bulman]], and [[Matt Hocking]]<ref name="Stevenage sign Hocking">{{cite news
| title = Stevenage sign Hocking
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stevenage/3852761.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2004-06-30
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> &ndash; as well as players from lower divisions such as [[Jon Nurse]] and [[Craig McAllister]].<ref name="Stevenage snap up Nurse">{{cite news
| title = Stevenage snap up Nurse
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stevenage/3801491.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2004-06-12
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref><ref name="Player Guide - Craig McAllister ">{{cite news
| title = Player Guide - Craig McAllister 
| url = http://www.boroguide.co.uk/players/m/mcallister_craig.php
| publisher = Boroguide
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> Westley also gave first-team opportunities to players who had progressed through the club's youth system, most notably [[George Boyd (footballer)|George Boyd]].<ref name="Player Guide - George Boyd ">{{cite news
| title = Player Guide - George Boyd
| url = http://www.boroguide.co.uk/players/b/boyd_george.php
| publisher = Boroguide
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> The squad originally struggled to perform, losing five games in the first eight games of the club's league campaign. However, two victories by wide margins against lowly opposition in the form of Farnborough and [[Northwich Victoria F.C.|Northwich Victoria]] respectively propelled the club into a mid-table position.<ref name="Farnborough 0-3 Stevenage">{{cite news
| title = Farnborough 0-3 Stevenage
| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/threecounties/content/articles/2004/09/21/farnborough_stevenage_210904_result.shtml
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2004-09-21
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref><ref name="Stevenage 4-1 Northwich">{{cite news
| title = Stevenage 4-1 Northwich
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/3659594.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2004-09-25
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> However, this was followed by two heavy defeats at the hands of [[York City F.C.|York City]] and [[Canvey Island F.C.|Canvey Island]] &ndash; the latter a 4&ndash;1 home defeat against part-time opposition.<ref name="York City 3-1 Stevenage">{{cite news
| title = York City 3-1 Stevenage
| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/threecounties/content/articles/2004/10/01/york_city_stevenage_0210_result.shtml
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2004-10-02
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref><ref name="Stevenage 1-4 Canvey Island">{{cite news
| title = Stevenage 1-4 Canvey Island
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/3697648.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2004-10-05
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> After the game, with hundreds of Stevenage fans calling for Westley to be sacked, he confronted fans in the [[Broadhall Way|East Terrace]] by saying he "would turn it around".<ref name="Manager Guide - Graham Westley">{{cite news
| title = Manager Guide - Graham Westley 
| url = http://www.boroguide.co.uk/players/managers/westley_graham.php
| publisher = Boroguide
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> Westley's side responded with four straight wins, and stayed within touching distance of the play-offs for several months. An important double over [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]] in March 2005,<ref name="Carlisle 1-2 Stevenage">{{cite news
| title = Carlisle 1-2 Stevenage
| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/threecounties/content/articles/2005/02/22/carlisle_stevenage_220205_result.shtml
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2005-02-22
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref><ref name="Stevenage 2-1 Carlisle">{{cite news
| title = Stevenage 2-1 Carlisle
| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/threecounties/content/articles/2005/03/04/stevenage_carlisle_050305_result.shtml
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2005-03-05
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> as well as crucial wins at [[Aldershot Town F.C.|Aldershot Town]], [[Woking F.C.|Woking]], and [[Crawley Town F.C.|Crawley Town]] meant that Stevenage went into the final day of the season needing to beat already relegated [[Leigh Genesis F.C.|Leigh RMI]], and had to rely on [[Tamworth F.C.|Tamworth]] to hold Morecambe, who were currently occupying the final play-off spot.<ref name="Crawley 1-2 Stevenage">{{cite news
| title = Crawley 1-2 Stevenage
| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/threecounties/content/articles/2005/04/19/stevenage_crawley_190405_result.shtml
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2005-04-19
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> Stevenage beat Leigh 2&ndash;0, whilst Tamworth held Morecambe to a goalless draw, ultimately meaning Westley's side had reached the play-offs on the final day of the season.<ref name="Stevenage 2-0 Leigh RMI">{{cite news
| title = Stevenage 2-0 Leigh RMI
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/4451721.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2005-04-23
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> Westley engineered two solid displays to ensure Stevenage overcame second-placed [[Hereford United F.C.|Hereford United]] 2&ndash;1 on aggregate, but lost 1&ndash;0 to Carlisle United at the [[Britannia Stadium]] in the final.<ref name="Stevenage 1-1 Hereford">{{cite news
| title = Stevenage 1-1 Hereford
| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/threecounties/content/articles/2005/04/28/stevenage_hereford_020505_result.shtml
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2005-05-02
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref><ref name="Hereford 0-1 Stevenage">{{cite news
| title = Hereford 0-1 Stevenage
| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/threecounties/content/articles/2005/05/05/hereford_stevenage_secondleg_060505_result.shtml
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2005-05-06
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref><ref name="Carlisle 1-0 Stevenage">{{cite news
| title = Carlisle 1-0 Stevenage
| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/threecounties/content/articles/2005/05/10/carlisle_stevenage_playoff_final_140505_result.shtml
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2005-05-14
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref>

The [[2005-06 in English football|2005&ndash;06]] season marked Westley's third season in charge as manager of the club, and although the club were consistent at [[Broadhall Way]] throughout the season, the side struggled for form away from home, winning just four games on the road all season.<ref name="Final 2005/2006 Football Conference Table">{{cite news
| title = Final 2005/2006 Football Conference Table
| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/league2.sd
| publisher = Soccerbase
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> Stevenage's poor away form was ultimately preventing the club from mounting any serious title challenge, and throughout the campaign Westley's side would often "lose the game before it began"<ref name="Southport 3-2 Stevenage">{{cite news
| title = Southport 3-2 Stevenage
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/4148474.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2005-08-20
| accessdate = 2010-06-06}}</ref> &ndash; in away games against [[Southport F.C.|Southport]], [[Morecambe F.C.|Morecambe]], and [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]] respectively, Westley's side trailed 3&ndash;0 before half-time.<ref name="Southport 3-2 Stevenage">{{cite news
| title = Southport 3-2 Stevenage
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/4148474.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2005-08-20
| accessdate = 2010-06-06}}</ref><ref name="Morecambe 4-1 Stevenage">{{cite news
| title = Morecambe 4-1 Stevenage
| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=465339
| publisher = Soccerbase
| date = 2005-09-24
| accessdate = 2010-06-06}}</ref><ref name="Burton Albion 3-1 Stevenage">{{cite news
| title = Burton Albion 3-1 Stevenage
| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=457786
| publisher = Soccerbase
| date = 2005-10-08
| accessdate = 2010-06-06}}</ref> Westley had also fallen out with striker [[Anthony Elding]], who was eventually sold to [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]] in January 2006.<ref name="Kettering win battle for Elding">{{cite news
| title = Kettering win battle for Elding
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stevenage/4616434.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2006-01-16
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> There were also increasingly frequent question marks surrounding the discipline of the squad under Westley's control, as Stevenage received fourteen red cards during the campaign, more than any other club in the league by some distance.<ref name="Stevenage 2005/2006 player appearances">{{cite news
| title = Stevenage 2005/2006 player appearances
| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/squad_season.sd
| publisher = Soccerbase
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> A 2&ndash;0 defeat away to relegation-threatened [[Forest Green Rovers F.C.|Forest Green Rovers]] on the final day of the season meant that Stevenage failed to reach the play-offs, finishing 6th in the table.<ref name="Forest Green 2-0 Stevenage">{{cite news
| title = Forest Green 2-0 Stevenage
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/4933584.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2006-04-29
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> After failing to reach the play-offs, Westley confirmed in May 2006 that he would leave the club when his contract expired in June, ending his three and a half year tenure with the Hertfordshire club.<ref name="Westley to leave Borough">{{cite news
| title = Westley to leave Borough
| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/threecounties/content/articles/2006/05/15/graham_westley_leaves_feature.shtml
| publisher = BBC Beds Herts and Bucks
| date = 2006-05-15
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref>

===Rushden & Diamonds===
He was appointed manager of [[Rushden & Diamonds F.C.|Rushden & Diamonds]] in December 2006, with the club sitting 22nd in the table, two points adrift of safety.<ref name="Rushden name Westley as new boss">{{cite news
| title = Rushden name Westley as new boss
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rushden_and_diamonds/6189787.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2006-12-18
| accessdate = 2007-10-05}}</ref> Westley's first game in charge of Rushden was a 1&ndash;0 victory away at [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]], as he set about ensuring safety.<ref name="Cambridge Utd 0-1 Rushden & Diamonds">{{cite news
| title = Cambridge Utd 0-1 Rushden & Diamonds
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/6205737.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2006-12-26
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> Westley secured the signatures of several players who he had previously managed at Stevenage; signing the likes of [[Jamie Cook]], [[David Perpetuini]], and [[Dino Maamria]].<ref name="Rushden swoop for striker Maamria">{{cite news
| title = Rushden swoop for striker Maamria
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rushden_and_diamonds/6320085.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2007-02-01
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> Westley also brought in the likes of Michael Bostwick and [[Chris Beardsley]] &ndash; younger players who he had previously written about in his weekly column in ''[[The Non-League Paper]]'' when he was out of work.<ref name="Diamonds secure Beardsley signing">{{cite news
| title = Diamonds secure Beardsley signing
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rushden_and_diamonds/6279009.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2007-01-19
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref><ref name="Diamonds sign Millwall's Bostwick">{{cite news
| title = Diamonds sign Millwall's Bostwick
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rushden_and_diamonds/6308089.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2007-01-28
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> Westley's newly assembled team secured five straight wins in the league, including wins away at the top two teams in the league at the time, [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]] and [[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.|Dagenham & Redbridge]].<ref name="Dag & Red 1-2 Rushden">{{cite news
| title = Dag & Red 1-2 Rushden
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/6327149.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2007-02-10
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> Despite managing an upturn in the form of the club, Westley was surprisingly sacked after a 2&ndash;2 draw at [[Aldershot Town F.C.|Aldershot Town]] in February 2007.<ref name="Rushden sack Westley after draw">{{cite news
| title = Rushden sack Westley after draw
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rushden_and_diamonds/6394305.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2007-02-25
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> He had taken the club from 22nd in the league to 12th in the space of two and a half months, and the club were on a seven match unbeaten run at the time. In total, he managed Rushden for 13 games; winning seven, drawing three and losing three. The reason behind Westley's sacking is unknown, but he was replaced two days later by [[Garry Hill]].<ref name="Hill named new Diamonds boss">{{cite news
| title = Hill named new Diamonds boss
| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/northamptonshire/content/articles/2007/02/27/diamonds_appoint_garry_hill_as_manager_feature.shtml
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2007-02-27
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref>

===Kettering Town===
Shortly after leaving Rushden, Westley was appointed [[caretaker manager]] of [[Conference North]] outfit [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]] for the rest of the [[2006<U+2013>07 in English football|2006&ndash;07]] season in April 2007.<ref name="Poppies appoint Westley">{{cite news
| title = Poppies appoint Westley
| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/northamptonshire/content/articles/2007/04/20/graham_westley_kettering_caretaker_boss_feature.shtml
| publisher = BBC Northamptonshire
| date = 2007-04-20
| accessdate = 2007-10-13}}</ref> Due to the date he joined, Westley was unable to bring any new players in to bolster the squad, with just two games remaining until the end of the season. His first game in charge was a 0&ndash;0 draw away to [[Stalybridge Celtic F.C.|Stalybridge Celtic]],<ref name="Stalybridge Celtic 0-0 Kettering">{{cite news
| title = Stalybridge Celtic 0-0 Kettering
| url = http://www.soccerfactsuk.co.uk/
| publisher = Soccerfactsuk
| accessdate = 2010-07-06}}</ref> shortly followed by a 1&ndash;0 loss to [[Alfreton Town F.C.|Alfreton Town]] at [[Rockingham Road]]<ref name="Kettering 0-1 Alfreton Town">{{cite news
| title = Kettering 0-1 Alfreton Town
| url = http://www.soccerfactsuk.co.uk/
| publisher = Soccerfactsuk
| accessdate = 2010-07-06}}</ref> &ndash; this was enough to ensure Kettering finished the season in second place.<ref name="English Conference North 2006-2007 : Table">{{cite news
| title = English Conference North 2006-2007 : Table
| url = http://www.statto.com/football/stats/england/conference-north/2006-2007
| publisher = Statto.com
| accessdate = 2010-07-06}}</ref> He managed Kettering in the play-offs, as they were beaten on penalties by [[Farsley Celtic F.C.|Farsley Celtic]] in the semi-final after a 1&ndash;1 aggregate scoreline over two legs,<ref name="Conference North/South play-offs">{{cite news
| title = Conference North/South play-offs
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/6620221.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2007-05-15
| accessdate = 2010-06-09}}</ref> he left shortly after when his short-term contract expired in May 2007, managing the club for a total of four games.<ref name="Kettering Town - Club History">{{cite news
| title = Kettering Town - Club History
| publisher = Kettering Town F.C.
| url = http://www.ketteringtownfc.co.uk/club_info.php?mode=history
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref>

===Return to Stevenage===
After almost a year without work in football, Westley surprisingly returned as Stevenage manager in May 2008 &ndash; two years after he had originally left.<ref name="Westley named as Stevenage boss">{{cite news
| title = Westley named as Stevenage boss
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stevenage/7380315.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2008-05-02
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> On his return, Westley stated he had come to "finish the job he started" &ndash; referring to trying to guide the club into the Football League for the first time in its history. He said that "the moment was right" for him to come back into football and that he "had some very good times at [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]] before".<ref name="Stevenage return delights Westley">{{cite news
| title = Stevenage return delights Westley
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stevenage/7388076.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2008-05-07
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> His appointment was met with a fair bit of scepticism by Stevenage fans, but Westley promised to deliver a winning team, playing attractive football.<ref name="Stevenage return delights Westley">{{cite news
| title = Stevenage return delights Westley
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stevenage/7388076.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2008-05-07
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> Westley started by completely overhauling the squad in the summer transfer window and brought in no fewer than twelve players in an attempt to mount a serious [[Conference National]] title challenge. Among those brought in were [[Gary Mills (footballer born 1981)|Gary Mills]] and [[David Bridges]], who Westley had managed during his short-stint at Kettering.<ref name="New signings confirmed">{{cite news
| title = New signings confirmed
| url = http://www.stevenageborofc.com/index_news_det.php?uk_newsOrder=Sorter_date&uk_newsDir=DESC&uk_newsPage=65&news_id=657
| publisher = Stevenage official site
| date = 2008-05-12
| accessdate = 2009-05-19}}</ref> He also signed Michael Bostwick and [[Mark Albrighton]], who he had also signed at [[Rushden & Diamonds F.C.|Rushden & Diamonds]].<ref name="Bostwick joins Boro">{{cite news
| title = Bostwick joins Boro
| url = http://www.stevenageborofc.com/index_news_det.php?uk_newsOrder=Sorter_date&uk_newsDir=DESC&uk_newsPage=65&news_id=666
| publisher = Stevenage official site
| date = 2008-05-20
| accessdate = 2009-05-19}}</ref><ref name="Albrighton signs">{{cite news
| title = Albrighton signs
| url = http://www.stevenageborofc.com/index_news_det.php?uk_newsOrder=Sorter_date&uk_newsDir=DESC&uk_newsPage=64&news_id=670
| publisher = Stevenage official site
| date = 2008-05-30
| accessdate = 2009-05-19}}</ref> Westley also secured the signatures of Andy Drury and [[Eddie Odhiambo]] respectively, both of which were players Westley had previously earmarked.<ref name="Stevenage add Drury to new signings">{{cite news
| title = Stevenage add Drury to new signings
| url = http://www.stevenageborofc.com/index_news_det.php?uk_newsOrder=Sorter_date&uk_newsDir=DESC&uk_newsPage=65&news_id=6621
| publisher = Stevenage official site
| date = 2008-05-16
| accessdate = 2009-05-19}}</ref><ref name="Borough capture Anaclet">{{cite news
| title = Borough capture Anaclet
| url = http://www.stevenageborofc.com/index_news_det.php?uk_newsOrder=Sorter_date&uk_newsDir=DESC&uk_newsPage=65&news_id=658
| publisher = Stevenage official site
| date = 2008-05-13
| accessdate = 2009-05-19}}</ref> 

Stevenage started the season poorly, losing 3 out of their first 4 games and conceding 13 goals in the process, including a 5&ndash;0 loss to [[Wrexham F.C.|Wrexham]] on the first day of the season.<ref name="Wrexham 5-0 Stevenage">{{cite news
| title = Wrexham 5-0 Stevenage
| url = http://www.stevenageborofc.com/pages_fixt_rec.php?s_archive_id=3&s_fixture_category=1&fixture_id=300
| publisher = Stevenage official site
| date = 2008-08-09
| accessdate = 2009-07-21}}</ref> The club secured its first victory under Westley in late August 2008, a 3&ndash;1 win away at [[Barrow A.F.C.|Barrow]],<ref name="Barrow 1-3 Stevenage">{{cite news
| title = Barrow 1-3 Stevenage
| url = http://www.stevenageborofc.com/pages_fixt_rec.php?s_archive_id=3&s_fixture_category=1&fixture_id=305
| publisher = Stevenage official site
| date = 2008-08-30
| accessdate = 2009-07-21}}</ref> before winning four games on the bounce in September.<ref name="Forest Green Rovers 0-3 Stevenage Borough">{{cite news
| title = Forest Green Rovers 0-3 Stevenage Borough
| url = http://www.stevenageborofc.com/pages_fixt_rec.php?s_archive_id=3&s_fixture_category=1&fixture_id=309
| publisher = Stevenage official site
| date = 2008-09-20
| accessdate = 2009-07-21}}</ref> However, through the first half of the club's [[2008-09 in English football|2008&ndash;09]] campaign, Westley's side were suffering from the same inconsistency that was common in his first spell as manager of the [[Hertfordshire]] side, losing three games on the trot in November &ndash; the last of which was a 2&ndash;1 home defeat to Wrexham, it was to be Stevenage's last defeat at [[Broadhall Way]] in the league for 18 months.<ref name="Stevenage Borough 1-2 Wrexham">{{cite news
| title = Stevenage Borough 1-2 Wrexham
| url = http://www.stevenageborofc.com/pages_fixt_rec.php?s_archive_id=3&s_fixture_category=1&fixture_id=320
| publisher = Stevenage official site
| date = 2008-11-29
| accessdate = 2009-07-21}}</ref> Westley brought in former player, [[Dino Maamria]] as first-team coach at the club. This, coupled with key signings during the campaign, such as [[Chris Day]], [[Mark Roberts (footballer born 1983)|Mark Roberts]], and [[Jon Ashton]], meant that Stevenage witnessed an up-turn in form half way through the campaign.<ref name="Two deadline day signings for Boro">{{cite news
| title = Two deadline day signings for Boro
| url = http://www.stevenageborofc.com/index_news_det.php?uk_newsOrder=Sorter_date&uk_newsDir=DESC&uk_newsPage=53&news_id=797
| publisher = Stevenage official site
| date = 2008-09-01
| accessdate = 2009-05-19}}</ref><ref name="News of signings and loans">{{cite news
| title = News of signings and loans
| url = http://www.stevenageborofc.com/index_news_det.php?uk_newsPage=29&news_id=1044
| publisher = Stevenage official site
| date = 2009-01-01
| accessdate = 2009-05-19}}</ref><ref name="Ashton move secured">{{cite news
| title = Ashton move secured
| url = http://www.stevenageborofc.com/index_news_det.php?news_id=1110
| publisher = Stevenage official site
| date = 2009-01-29
| accessdate = 2009-05-19}}</ref> A 24 game unbeaten run stretching from December 2008 to April 2009, as well as winning crucial games towards the latter stages of the season, ultimately meant that Westley's men made the [[2008<U+2013>09 Football Conference#Play-offs|Conference National play-offs]], finishing in the last play-off place.<ref name="Mansfield Town 2-1 Stevenage Borough">{{cite news
| title = Mansfield Town 2-1 Stevenage Borough
| url = http://www.stevenageborofc.com/pages_fixt_rec.php?s_archive_id=3&s_fixture_category=1&fixture_id=345
| publisher = Stevenage official site
| date = 2009-04-26
| accessdate = 2009-07-22}}</ref> Despite taking a 3&ndash;1 lead into the second leg, Stevenage lost 4&ndash;3 overall on aggregate to Cambridge United.<ref name="Stevenage Borough 3-1 Cambridge United">{{cite news
| title = Stevenage Borough 3-1 Cambridge United
| url = http://www.stevenageborofc.com/pages_fixt_rec.php?s_archive_id=3&s_fixture_category=1&fixture_id=385
| publisher = Stevenage official site
| date = 2009-04-30
| accessdate = 2009-07-22}}</ref> Westley did, however, enjoy success in the [[FA Trophy]] when he led the side out at [[Wembley Stadium]] in front of 27,102 as Stevenage beat [[York City F.C.|York City]] 2&ndash;0 in the [[2009 FA Trophy Final|Final]]. The win was Westley's first taste of success as manager of Stevenage.<ref name="Stevenage Borough 2-0 York City">{{cite news
| title = Stevenage 2-0 York
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/8036407.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2009-05-09
| accessdate = 2009-07-22}}</ref> After the game, it was announced that Westley was to stay on as manager for another year.<ref name="Manager Guide - Graham Westley">{{cite news
| title = Manager Guide - Graham Westley 
| url = http://www.boroguide.co.uk/players/managers/westley_graham.php
| publisher = Boroguide
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref>

The majority of the squad that performed so well in the second half of the club's 2008&ndash;09 campaign were retained, with very little transfer activity in comparison to previous seasons under Westley. [[Steve Morison]], the club's top goalscorer for the past three seasons, moved to [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] for a fee of <U+00A3>130,000,<ref name="Millwall agree deal for Morison">{{cite news
| title = Millwall agree deal for Morison
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stevenage/8052772.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2009-05-15
| accessdate = 2009-05-15}}</ref></center> while both [[John Martin (English footballer)|John Martin]] and [[Calum Willock]] were released by Westley in late May 2009.<ref name="John Martin released">{{cite news
| title = John Martin released
| url = http://www.stevenageborofc.com/index_news_det.php?news_id=1397
| publisher = Stevenage official site
| date = 2009-05-20
| accessdate = 2009-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stevenageborofc.com/index_news_det.php?news_id=1400|title=Willock released|date=2009-05-21|publisher=Stevenage F.C.|accessdate=2009-07-02}}</ref> Midfielder Gary Mills was the last departure of the close season; rejecting a contract and instead opting to join fellow Conference rivals [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]].<ref name="Stags swoop for Stevenage's Mills">{{cite news
| title = Stags swoop for Stevenage's Mills
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/mansfield_town/8068985.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2009-05-26
| accessdate = 2009-07-11}}</ref></center> Five players joined the club during the close season. [[Charlie Griffin]] was the first signing of the season, joining Stevenage from [[Salisbury City F.C.|Salisbury City]] on a free transfer. [[Yemi Odubade]], [[Chris Beardsley]], and [[Joel Byrom]] signed for the club shortly after; the latter commanding a transfer fee of <U+00A3>15,000.<ref name="Odubade completes Stevenage move">{{cite news
| title = Odubade completes Stevenage move
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stevenage/8049842.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2009-05-14
| accessdate = 2009-05-14}}</ref></center><ref name="Stevenage sign midfielder Byrom">{{cite news
| title = Stevenage sign midfielder Byrom
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stevenage/8053660.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2009-05-16
| accessdate = 2009-05-17}}</ref></center> Westley had previously managed Beardsley at Rushden & Diamonds and Kettering Town. The last signing of pre-season was [[Stacy Long]]; who joined the club on a free transfer from [[Ebbsfleet United F.C.|Ebbsfleet United]]. No players departed the club during the season, with [[Tim Sills]] the only addition &ndash; signing for an undisclosed fee from [[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]] in January 2010.<ref name="Sills deal completed">{{cite news
| title = Sills deal completed
| url = http://www.stevenageborofc.com/index_news_det.php?news_id=1689
| publisher = Stevenage F.C.
| date = 2010-01-15
| accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref> 

{{Quote box | width=30% | align=right | quote= "When you've put as much work in as we have over the last couple of years to build a team, to build a successful squad, to see it come to fruition is fantastic." |source= <small> Graham Westley, on [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]] securing promotion to [[the Football League]] in April 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stevenage/8630986.stm|title=I'm pleased for Stevenage Borough fans - Wallace |publisher=BBC Sport |date= 20 April 2010 |accessdate= 23 May 2010}}</ref> </small> }}
Stevenage's league campaign got off to a typically patchy start; with the side recording just one win from their first five games of the season. Following a 2&ndash;1 defeat to [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]] in August 2009,<ref name="Oxford United 2-1 Stevenage Borough">{{cite news
| title = Oxford United 2-1 Stevenage Borough
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/8208155.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2009-08-22
| accessdate = 2009-08-22}}</ref> the team went on a 17 game unbeaten run that stretched four months from August to December 2009, propelling the club into the top two. Unlike in previous seasons, the club were performing strongly away from home, and secured victories at the likes of [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] and Mansfield Town.<ref name="Luton 0-1 Stevenage">{{cite news
| title = Luton 0-1 Stevenage
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/8271233.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2009-09-29
| accessdate = 2009-09-29}}</ref> A 4&ndash;1 victory against [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]] on [[New Year's Day]] ultimately meant that Stevenage hit top-spot for the first time in the season.<ref name="Stevenage 4-1 Cambridge Utd">{{cite news
| title = Stevenage 4-1 Cambridge Utd
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/8423540.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2010-01-01
| accessdate = 2010-01-01}}</ref> However, two defeats on the road within the space of a week in February meant that rivals Oxford United had an eight&ndash;point lead going into March 2010. The team responded well, winning eight games on the bounce; including an important 1&ndash;0 victory over Oxford United in late March, subsequently replacing Oxford at the top of the table.<ref name="Stevenage Borough 1-0 Oxford United">{{cite news
| title = Stevenage Borough 1-0 Oxford United
| url = http://www.stevenageborofc.com/index_news_det.php?news_id=1800
| publisher = Stevenage official site
| date = 2010-03-30
| accessdate = 2010-03-30}}</ref> Borough brushed aside a late challenge from Luton Town, securing promotion to the Football League with two games to spare following a 2&ndash;0 win against [[Kidderminster Harriers F.C.|Kidderminster Harriers]] at [[Aggborough]].<ref name="Kidderminster 0-2 Stevenage">{{cite news
| title = Kidderminster 0-2 Stevenage
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/8618329.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = 2010-04-17
| accessdate = 2010-04-17}}</ref> The team won their last six games of the league campaign without conceding a single goal, and recorded 42 points from a possible 45 from their last 15 league fixtures.<ref name="Stevenage Borough 1-0 York City">{{cite news
| title = Stevenage Borough 1-0 York City
| url = http://www.stevenageborofc.com/index_news_det.php?news_id=1848
| publisher = Stevenage F.C.
| date = 2010-04-24
| accessdate = 2010-04-24}}</ref> Stevenage finished the season having amassed a total of 99 points from 44 games, winning the league by 11 points, with Westley winning many plaudits for the way he had secured promotion despite considerably less resources than a lot of the teams in the division.<ref name="Conference Table">{{cite news
| title =  Conference Table 
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/conference_table/default.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| accessdate = 2010-04-24}}</ref> The promotion means Westley has led Stevenage to [[the Football League]] for the first time in their history, as well as managing a Football League team for the first time in his managerial career. Westley also guided the club to another FA Trophy [[2010 FA Trophy Final|Final]]; this time losing 2&ndash;1 after extra-time against Barrow at Wembley Stadium.<ref name="Stevenage Borough 1-2 Barrow AET">{{cite news
| title = Stevenage Borough 1-2 Barrow AET
| url = http://www.stevenageborofc.com/index_news_det.php?news_id=1868
| publisher = Stevenage Official site
| date = 2010-05-08
| accessdate = 2010-05-08}}</ref> At the end of the season, Westley signed a new two-year contract; keeping him contracted to the club until 2012.<ref name="Westley's new two-year deal confirmed">{{cite news
| title = Westley's new two-year deal confirmed
| url = http://www.stevenageborofc.com/index_news_det.php?news_id=1885
| publisher = Stevenage Official site
| date = 2010-05-29
| accessdate = 2010-05-29}}</ref> On signing the new deal, Westley said "I am grateful for all the support that we have all been given in the past two years. I am delighted to have the opportunity to manage the launch of the club into the Football League".<ref name="Westley's new two-year deal confirmed">{{cite news
| title = Westley's new two-year deal confirmed
| url = http://www.stevenageborofc.com/index_news_det.php?news_id=1885
| publisher = Stevenage Official site
| date = 2010-05-29
| accessdate = 2010-05-29}}</ref> In his first two seasons back at the club, from May 2008 to May 2010, Westley has been in charge for 114 games, winning a total of 70 games &ndash; recording a win percentage of 61.40%.<ref name="Graham Westley's managerial career">{{cite news
| title = Graham Westley's managerial career
| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/managers2.sd?managerid=1850
| publisher = Soccerbase
| accessdate = 2010-06-05}}</ref>

Similarly to the club's successful campaign the season before, but in complete contrast to his first tenure at the club, the [[2010-11 in English football|2010&ndash;11]] season under Westley has witnessed a "five in, five out" policy regarding transfer activity &ndash; with roughly five players joining the club, while roughly five players leave the club in the close season.<ref name="Latest squad news">{{cite news
| title = Latest squad news
| url = http://212.113.133.41/stevenageborofc.com/index_news_det.php?uk_newsPage=2&news_id=1884
| publisher = Stevenage Official site
| date = 2010-05-28
| accessdate = 2010-06-09}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Westley writes a weekly column in ''[[The Non-League Paper]]'', sharing his views and experiences on the non-league game.<ref name="Non-League battle kicks off as ex-employee launches rival">{{cite news
| title = Non-League battle kicks off as ex-employee launches rival
| url = http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=38656
| work = Press Gazette
| date = 2007-08-31
| accessdate = 2010-05-24}}</ref> He is also the chief executive of the Aimita Corporation, an organisation that provides performance management consulting.<ref name="Westley puts his faith in the right attitude">{{cite news
| title = Westley puts his faith in the right attitude
| url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2394935/Westley-puts-his-faith-in-the-right-attitude.html
| publisher = ''The Daily Telegraph''
| date = 2003-01-23
| accessdate = 2010-05-24}}</ref> Westley has also gained a [[Master of Arts (postgraduate)|Master of Arts]] degree in company direction.<ref name="Westley happy to move on">{{cite news
| title = Westley happy to move on
| url = http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/westley-happy-to-move-on-609056.html
| publisher = Independent Sport
| date = 2003-01-31
| accessdate = 2010-06-09}}</ref><ref name="I will make the Sun shine">{{cite news
| title = I will make the Sun shine
| url = http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/sport/football/article197728.ece
| publisher = The Sun.co.uk
| accessdate = 2003-01-04
| accessdate = 2010-07-04}}</ref>

